<section xml:id="heaps_vocabulary"
         xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
  <title>Vocabulary</title>
  <p>
    <dl>
      <li>
        <title>binary tree</title>
        <p>
          <idx>
            <h>binary tree</h>
          </idx> A tree in which each node has at most two children.</p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <title>complete tree</title>
        <p>
          <idx>
            <h>complete tree</h>
          </idx> A tree in which all levels are completely filled except possibly the last level, which must be filled from left to right.</p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <title>heap</title>
        <p>
          <idx>
            <h>heap</h>
          </idx> A complete binary tree where each node is smaller than or equal to its children (min-heap) or larger than or equal to its children (max-heap).</p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <title>heap property</title>
        <p>
          <idx>
            <h>heap property</h>
          </idx> The property that a heap must satisfy, which is that each node is smaller than or equal to its children (min-heap) or larger than or equal to its children (max-heap).</p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <title>height (tree)</title>
        <p>
          <idx>
            <h>height</h>
            <h>tree</h>
          </idx> The number of edges on the longest path from the root to a leaf in a tree.</p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <title>max heap</title>
        <p>
          <idx>
            <h>max heap</h>
          </idx> A heap where every node is larger than or equal to its children and thus the largest value is at the top.</p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <title>min heap</title>
        <p>
          <idx>
            <h>min heap</h>
          </idx> A heap where every node is smaller than or equal to its children and thus the smallest value is at the top.</p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <title>priority queue</title>
        <p>
          <idx>
            <h>priority queue</h>
          </idx> A data structure that maintains a set of elements with associated priorities and allows for efficient retrieval of the highest (or lowest) priority element.</p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <title>shape property (heap)</title>
        <p>
          <idx>
            <h>shape property</h>
            <h>heap</h>
          </idx> The property that a heap must satisfy, which is that all levels of the tree are filled except possibly the last level, which must be filled from left to right.</p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <title>tree</title>
        <p>
          <idx>
            <h>tree</h>
          </idx> A data structure consisting of nodes connected by edges. Each node has exactly one parent (node that points to it), except for the root node.</p>
      </li>
    </dl>
  </p>
</section>